5: You've got to be kidding me!
9:
We heard the same report, didn't
we? The Vesta aren't hostile to
us—they just can't leave the
settlement right now!
12:
How can you possibly send out
troops when you know all that?!
15:
The deployment of troops has
already been voted upon by the
High Council—the matter is settled. I
can't divulge any more than that.
22:
All I can offer at this juncture is my
own personal opinion on the matter.
25:
If the Vesta won't demilitarize, we
simply have no other option. Our
hands are tied.
28:
I can understand and sympathize
with their motives. They wish to save
their brethren, yes? It would not be
impossible to accommodate their
requests.
31:
However, would that not also be
possible after they have thrown
down their weapons and submitted
to the authority of the Guild?
39:
Speaking frankly, this seems like
cowardice on the Guild's part—they
needlessly fear a surprise attack
from the Vesta.
43:
You do not fully comprehend the
situation.
46:
Palpebra is a town that celebrates
individual liberty. The prosperity we
enjoy now comes precisely from the
diversity of people we have allowed
in.
48:
But that freedom extends only to
individuals—a gathering of an
armed force outside our city
imperils the order we have so
painstakingly forged.
52:
Say it like it is—you're afraid of the
Vesta, right?
56:
Yes. That's correct. They are an
unknown military force stationed
right at our door. To not fear them
would be folly.
60: In that case, blood's gonna flow.
66:
Nope. It's a statement—the Vesta
are tough as hell, and they're used
to warfare. I can see where this'll
lead, is all.
69:
What do you think about this,
Zekhel? This is exactly the situation
you wanted to avoid, isn't it?
73:
No one will benefit from this, and
both sides stand to lose so much...
77:
Yep. I hear you, kid. I know this, and
the Guild knows it. But it's not
enough.
79:
They've done the calculations, and
even factoring in potential losses,
this is actually the cheaper option.
82:
Cheaper?!
They're thinking of money at a time
like this?!
87:
What do you intend to do about the
Purgers, then?
89:
They're not dragons, nor are they a
foreign state. They are a brand new
form of enemy, and they ARE
coming. Is Palpebra ready?
93:
I had heard of this "prophecy."
Zekhel, what do you make of it?
98:
Personally, I think it's worth hearing
them out. Frankly, I've got a bad
feeling about it.
101:
But, uh, it really doesn't matter what
the two of us say, does it? We don't
make decisions on our own, after all.
106:
We need more time.
We can talk to the Vesta.
110:
Y-yes, please wait! Give us another
chance, if we can just negotiate with
them—
114:
And while you "negotiate," you give
the enemy time to build up their
military might.
117:
...You have until tomorrow. That is all
the latitude I can afford you.
127:
If you truly wish to save them, then I
urge you to tread carefully.
131:
First, focus on removing the threat.
That is what concerns the Guild the
most.
140:
Thank you for sharing this
information with us.
144:
But the matter is clear—the Vesta
shall fight down to the last warrior.
148:
That... But...
Won't you at least listen to the
Guild's demands?
151:
They do not trust us—and we cannot
trust them. There is no guarantee
they will keep their word.
153:
Why would they? If we were to lay
down our arms, what profit is there
in granting mercy to us?
156:
The pleas of the weak always fall on
deaf ears.
164:
The Vesta will not willingly give up
our strength. We will not become
weak.
171:
And here I was thinking I'd finally
gotten a chance to talk to you...
Looks like the timing's all wrong.
173:
So, how do you intend to deal with
this problem? I suppose you always
have the option of NOT dealing with
it too...
176:
Now that I'm here, I can provide you
with information for your quest. In
the grand scheme of things, this
world isn't all that important—
180:
I will not abandon them.
If we leave now, we won't be able to
save the remaining Vesta.
184:
You'll have to pardon me for that
little test there. I figured that's what
you would say.
187:
In that case, we'll be helping out
Memram, yes?
192:
That would inevitably mean
crossing blades with the Guild...
194:
As Nimbus said, the Vesta are
indeed formidable warriors... In fact,
strife might be all they've ever
known.
200:
From what Princess Lilith told me, it
seems that beastfolk on my home
world occupy a rather low place in
the social hierarchy.
202:
Consider also that war and conflict
were commonplace there—for the
Vesta, might alone was the only way
for them to secure their place and
dignity in the world.
205:
It would be impossible to ask them
to give that up.
210:
Despite this whole troop
deployment thing, I'm sure the
higher-ups in Palpebra would prefer
to have peace...
212:
Problem is the Vesta are a wild card
to the Guild... Unfamiliar and
untrustworthy.
214:
Maybe we could play up how
dangerous the Vesta are? Convince
the Guild that they're better left
alone?
218:
Alk, Stella.
What do you two think?
226:
I think choosing one side would
mean abandoning the other. I know
that's the wrong way to think about
it, but—
234:
You're completely right, Stella. Plus,
not choosing sides would mean that
both sides suffer as well.
238:
Maybe it's not possible to resolve
this without someone getting hurt...
But there HAS to be a better way
than this!
241:
I intend to look for it—until the very
end.
245:
Just what exactly do you have in
mind?
249:
...What if we're thinking about this
the wrong way?
